r chasing the eclipse to China once again.  And while this trip was much better than last year\'s expedition, we were plagued with bad weather on eclipse day.  Across eastern China, thousands of chasers pulled all-nighters and bit their nails down to the skin watching the satellite images cast doom and gloom on our hopes of clear skies.  Just hours before the eclipse began, I decided there was no clear advantage to running, and we stayed at Naked Retreats in Moganshan to try our luck.  And while Shanghai was drenched with rain, and other \"best sites\" were completely clouded out, we experienced one of the most dramatic eclipses of the last 20 years.  Through blankets of rolling mist and fog we caught multiple glimpses of totality through holes in the sky.  The video is awesome!  Just goes to show that while clear skies is what you hope for, nature will always surprize you with its wonders.  Not what I was expecting - but completely satisfied.  \r\n\r\nWhile I prepare my images and video for the complete report, check out these links: \r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.theglobeandmail.com/search/?query=solar+eclipse&x=0&y=0\"target=\"-blank\">The Globe & Mail</a>  -  click on \"Canada\'s Eclipse Chaser\"\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.boston.com/bigpicture/2009/07/the_longest_solar_eclipse_of_t.html\"target=\"-blank\">The Boston Globe</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://s10.photobucket.com/albums/a120/alsonwong/China%202009/?action=view&current=DSC_0002Crop800.jpg\"target=\"blank\">Alson Wong Images</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://spaceweather.com/eclipses/gallery_22jul09.htm\"target=\"-blank\">Space Weather</a>\r\n','The Misty Eclipse!  ',0,'Through blankets of rolling mist and fog, we witnessed the grand Total Eclipse of 2009. Read the preliminary report.  ','inherit','open','open','','1509-revision-7','','','2009-08-05 10:15:22','2009-08-05 14:15:22','',1509,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1509-revision-7',0,'revision','',0),(1521,5,'2009-08-06 18:23:49','2009-08-06 22:23:49','<p style=\"text-align: center;\">This was a wild and successful eclipse chase!  Read the Trip Report, see the photos &amp; video <a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/tripreport/south-america-%E2%80%93-11-july-2010\" target=\"_self\">here</a>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Animation of the Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2010jul11t.gif\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n\r\nYou have to get into that little black dot!!\r\n\r\nThis is the next major Total Eclipse to come to Earth.  It is visible almost entirely from the Pacific Ocean ONLY!  It makes landfall on a few, remote islands near Tahiti - and on Easter Island, of all places.  Many cruises to see totality have been planned and many are already fully booked.  This is an expensive eclipse to chase because of the difficult location. But what is money for?  I am booked on a private charter aircraft out of Argentina that will fly into the eclipse at 35,000 feet!  We are guaranteed clear skies!   <a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/news/one-seat-available-eclipse-observation-flightpatagoniajuly-2010\">Click here for details.</a>\r\n\r\nFor more on this eclipse, visit Fred Espenak\'s dedicated NASA web page <a href=\"http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEmono/TSE2010/TSE2010.html\" target=\"_blank\">here.</a>','Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010',0,'This is the next big one! ','publish','open','open','','total-solar-eclipse-of-11-july-2010','','http://eclipseguy.dev/tripreport/south-america-%E2%80%93-11-july-2010\nhttp://eclipseguy.dev/news/one-seat-available-eclipse-observation-flightpatagoniajuly-2010','2011-07-20 16:45:20','2011-07-20 20:45:20','',0,'http://eclipseguy.dev/?p=1521',0,'post','',0),(1522,5,'2009-08-06 13:08:35','2009-08-06 17:08:35','Zee blurb here.  ','Annular Eclipse of 15 January 2010',0,'Details','inherit','open','open','','1521-revision','','','2009-08-06 13:08:35','2009-08-06 17:08:35','',1521,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1521-revision',0,'revision','',0),(1520,5,'2009-08-05 09:35:55','2009-08-05 13:35:55','Where will you be?\r\n\r\n<h3>2010</h3>\r\n<strong>January 15</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. Indian Ocean. Landfall in East Africa to Burma.\r\n\r\n<strong>July 11</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 5:20. South Pacific Ocean. Landfall through The Cook Islands, French Polynesia, Easter Island &amp; extreme southern Chili.\r\n<h3>2011</h3>\r\n<strong>January 4</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Europe. North Africa.\r\n<strong>June 1</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Greenland. High Arctic.\r\n<strong>July 1</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Southern Ocean. New Saros begins!\r\n<strong>November 25</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Antarctica.\r\n<h3>2012</h3>\r\n<strong>May 20</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. East China Sea. Japan, N. Pacific. Western U.S.\r\n<strong>November 13</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 4:02. N. Australia. Pacific Ocean.\r\n<h3>2013</h3>\r\n<strong>May 10</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. N. Australia. Pacific Ocean.\r\n<strong>November 3</strong> - Hybrid Eclipse (Annular/Total). Atlantic Ocean. Central Africa.\r\n<h3>2014</h3>\r\n<strong>April 29</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. Australia. Southern Ocean.\r\n<strong>October 23</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. N. America.\r\n<h3>2015</h3>\r\n<strong>March 20</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 2:47. North Pole. Norwegian Sea.\r\n<strong>September 13</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. S. Africa. Antarctica.\r\n<h3>2016</h3>\r\n<strong>March 9</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 4:09.  Sumatra, Borneo, Sulawesi, Pacific Ocean.\r\n<strong>September 1</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse.  Africa.  Indian Ocean.\r\n<h3>2017</h3>\r\n<strong>February 26</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. Pacific. Chile. Argentina. Atlantic. Africa.\r\n<strong>August 21</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 2:40. United States.','Eclipse Calendar',0,'','inherit','open',