f=\"http://spaceweather.com/eclipses/gallery_22jul09.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Space Weather</a>','The Misty Eclipse!  ',0,'Through blankets of rolling mist and fog we witnessed the grand Total Eclipse of 2009. Read the preliminary report.  NEW VIDEO!!!','inherit','open','open','','1509-revision-21','','','2010-06-12 15:06:37','2010-06-12 19:06:37','',1509,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1509-revision-21',0,'revision','',0),(1768,5,'2010-04-17 19:43:16','2010-04-17 23:43:16','','se2013nov03h',0,'','inherit','open','open','','se2013nov03h','','','2010-04-17 19:43:16','2010-04-17 23:43:16','',551,'http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2013nov03h.gif',0,'attachment','image/gif',0),(1769,5,'2010-01-17 17:04:33','2010-01-17 21:04:33','Where will you be?\r\n\r\n<h3>2010</h3>\r\n<strong>January 15</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. Indian Ocean. Landfall in East Africa to Burma.  <a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/news/spectacular-annular-eclipse-in-january-2010\">\r\nMore.</a>\r\n\r\n<strong>July 11</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 5:20. South Pacific Ocean. Landfall through The Cook Islands, French Polynesia, Easter Island &amp; extreme southern Chili. <a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/total-solar-eclipse-of-11-july-2010\">More.</a> \r\n<h3>2011</h3>\r\n<strong>January 4</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Europe. North Africa.\r\n<strong>June 1</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Greenland. High Arctic.\r\n<strong>July 1</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Southern Ocean. New Saros begins!\r\n<strong>November 25</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. Antarctica.\r\n<h3>2012</h3>\r\n<strong>May 20</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. East China Sea. Japan, N. Pacific. Western U.S.\r\n<strong>November 13</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 4:02. N. Australia. Pacific Ocean.\r\n<h3>2013</h3>\r\n<strong>May 10</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. N. Australia. Pacific Ocean.\r\n<strong>November 3</strong> - Hybrid Eclipse (Annular/Total). Atlantic Ocean. Central Africa.\r\n<h3>2014</h3>\r\n<strong>April 29</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. Australia. Southern Ocean.\r\n<strong>October 23</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. N. America.\r\n<h3>2015</h3>\r\n<strong>March 20</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 2:47. North Pole. Norwegian Sea.\r\n<strong>September 13</strong> - Partial Solar Eclipse. S. Africa. Antarctica.\r\n<h3>2016</h3>\r\n<strong>March 9</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 4:09.  Sumatra, Borneo, Sulawesi, Pacific Ocean.\r\n<strong>September 1</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse.  Africa.  Indian Ocean.\r\n<h3>2017</h3>\r\n<strong>February 26</strong> - Annular Solar Eclipse. Pacific. Chile. Argentina. Atlantic. Africa.\r\n<strong>August 21</strong> - TOTAL Solar Eclipse. Max. Duration 2:40. United States.','Eclipse Calendar',0,'','inherit','open','open','','551-revision-41','','','2010-01-17 17:04:33','2010-01-17 21:04:33','',551,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/551-revision-41',0,'revision','',0),(2381,5,'2012-03-24 23:04:39','2012-03-25 03:04:39','<a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/tripreport/outback-02-december-2002\"></a>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">I guarantee you that there are no veteran eclipse chasers spending time worrying about the end of the world in December 2012.  That\'s because we have a very important meeting in November.  A meeting with the Solar System.  A Total Solar Eclipse is the most spectacular natural event that you can witness from Earth.  And not even the Mayans can mess that up!</p>\r\n\r\nHere we go again:\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/TSE2012pp2a.JPG\" alt=\"TSE2012_path\" width=\"500\" height=\"375\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">The dark blue line is the path of the Total Eclipse 13 November 2012.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nIt\'s very common for the Moon\'s shadow to cross lots of ocean and hardly any land.  After all, the Earth is mostly water.  But this is only a bonus for whales and the odd albatross - not eclipse chasers!  Marine expeditions are tough and expensive, and almost totally out of reach.  But the Universe does frequently open a crack in the door so we can look through, and this year the light shines on Australia.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/auzzy2012_googlemap.jpg\" alt=\"TSE2012_google\" width=\"600\" height=\"400\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>You can see the sun\'s corona for a few minutes - at sunrise -  from a tiny patch of land in the northeast.</blockquote>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/auzzy_path2012.jpg\" alt=\"TSE2012_auzzy_path\" width=\"600\" height=\"400\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>Thousands of chasers from around the globe will fill up the streets and marinas and beaches between Port Douglas and Cairns.</blockquote>\r\nWe all saw a mind-bogglingly-beautiful sunset eclipse in the middle of the <a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/tripreport/outback-02-december-2002\" target=\"_self\">Outback in 2002,</a> and we are thrilled to be returning for a morning eclipse on the ocean.  A complimentary pairing of Auzzy eclipses to be sure.  While the desert eclipse was adventure travel at its best: remote - arduous - extreme - the ocean eclipse is the opposite - local - luxurious - relaxed - falling among a handful of upscale, coastal villages that thrive from tourism and proximity to the Great Barrier Reef.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/havens_overhead.jpg\" alt=\"TSE2012_havens\" width=\"600\" height=\"400\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>This is Tropical Havens - south of Port Douglas.  Eclipse chasing in style!   For once!!</blockquote>\r\nIt\'s hard to tell from overhead - but this cluster of villas is one of the sweet spots in the Universe!  On eclipse morning, all we have to do is get up - put the coffee on - and walk outside.   The eclipse comes\r\nto our beachfront!  There are 8 of us in my villa - some who have never seen an eclipse before, and some I have covered the globe with already.  In the days around the eclipse, we\'ll snorkel the Reef, hike the rainforest, and kickback Queensland style!  And ... do I hear New Zealand calling?\r\n\r\nNever seen an eclipse?  Wanna live for once?  It\'s not too late.  <a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/contact\" target=\"_self\">Contact me</a> now so you don\'t waste your life doing the same old thing.','Total Eclipse in 2012',0,'There is a Total Eclipse in 2012! \r\nCan you guess where? ','inherit','open','open','','2349-revision-28','','','2012-03-24 23:04:39','2012-03-25 03:04:39','',2349,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/2349-revision-28',0,'revision','',0),(1773,5,'2010-01-03 16:05:56','2010-01-03 20:05:56','<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Animation of the Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2010jul11t.gif\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n\r\nYou have to get into that little black dot!! \r\n\r\nThis is the next major Total Eclipse to come to Earth.  It is visible almost entirely from the Pacific Ocean ONLY!  It makes landfall on a few, remote islands near Tahiti - and on Easter Island, of all places.  Many cruises to see totality have been planned and many are already fully booked.  This is an expensive eclipse to chase because of the difficult location. But what is money for?  I am booked on a private charter aircraft out of Argentina that will fly into the eclipse at 35,000 feet!  We are guaranteed clear skies!  And I have one seat available right now if you want to join this expedition.  <a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/news/one-seat-available-eclipse-observation-flightpatagoniajuly-2010\">Click here for details.</a>\r\n\r\nFor more on this eclipse, visit Fred Espenak\'s dedicated NASA web page <a href=\"http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEmono/TSE2010/TSE2010.html\"target=\"_blank\">here.</a>  \r\n\r\n ','Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010',0,'This is the next big one! ','inherit','open','open','','1521-revision-21','','','2010-01-03 16:05:56','2010-01-03 20:05:56','',1521,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1521-revision-21',0,'revision','',0),(1774,5,'2010-06-11 18:16:16','2010-06-11 22:16:16','On 11 July 2010, a Total Solar Eclipse will be visible from a long corridor that spans the southern Pacific Ocean.  Tahiti will be teeming with eclipse seekers and adventurers taking to the sea in cruise liners and boarding flights to remote Tuamotu Islands.  Easter Island will also be packed to its shores with human eyes looking skyward.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Animation of the Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2010jul11t.gif\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n\r\nBut at the end of the eclipse day, the Moon\'s shadow crosses extreme southern Chile/Argentina where an organization called Eclipse-City will operate a private charter to fly into the path of the eclipse in mid air and intercept the shadow at  35, 000 feet.  This is where I will be!  It\'s my first observation from an aircraft!  Miles above the clouds, we are guaranteed a perfect view!  From this unique vantage point, we will see approximately 3:50 of Totality.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path.jpg\"></a><a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path2.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1716 aligncenter\" title=\"Microsoft Word - July 2009 Patagonia English\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path2.jpg\" alt=\"Microsoft Word - July 2009 Patagonia English\" width=\"450\" height=\"375\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\nIn the weeks prior to the eclipse, I will be visiting Peru for the first time.  I land in Lima - visit Puno - Lake Titicaca - then take the train through the Andes to Cuzco where I will embark on the famous Inca Trail hike up to Machu Picchu.  This spectacular trek takes three days and is one of the most intense hikes of my eclipse chasing career!  Amazing!  Then it\'s back to Lima before making my way through Buenos Aires and on to El Calafate where our eclipse flight takes off on July 11.  This is the last total eclipse until the end of 2012 so it had better be a good one!\r\n\r\nCome back later in the summer to see all the new eclipse video and expedition photography.\r\n\r\nYou must see a Total Eclipse of the Sun from the air before you die!','Eclipse Chasing Again! ',0,'A lifetime of eclipse chasing continues this summer with a spectacular observation from 35,000 feet. ','inherit','open','open','','1636-revision-38','','','2010-06-11 18:16:16','2010-06-11 22:16:16','',1636,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1636-revision-38',0,'revision','',0),(1775,5,'2010-06-11 18:20:58','2010-06-11 22:20:58','On 11 July 2010, a Total Solar Eclipse will be visible from a long corridor that spans the southern Pacific Ocean.  Tahiti will be teeming with eclipse seekers and adventurers taking to the sea in cruise liners and boarding flights to remote Tuamotu Islands.  Easter Island will also be packed to its shores with human eyes looking skyward.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Animation of the Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2010jul11t.gif\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n\r\nBut at the end of the eclipse day, the Moon\'s shadow crosses extreme southern Chile/Argentina where an organization called Eclipse-City will operate a private charter to fly into the path of the eclipse in mid air and intercept the shadow at  35, 000 feet.  This is where I will be!  It\'s my first observation from an aircraft!  Miles above the clouds, we are guaranteed a perfect view!  From this unique vantage point, we will see approximately 3:50 of Totality.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path.jpg\"></a><a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path2.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1716 aligncenter\" title=\"Microsoft Word - July 2009 Patagonia English\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path2.jpg\" alt=\"Microsoft Word - July 2009 Patagonia English\" width=\"450\" height=\"375\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\nIn the weeks prior to the eclipse, I will be visiting Peru for the first time.  I land in Lima - visit Puno - Lake Titicaca - then take the train through the Andes to Cuzco where I will embark on the famous Inca Trail hike up to Machu Picchu.  This spectacular trek takes three days and is one of the most intense hikes of my eclipse chasing career!  Amazing!  Then it\'s back to Lima before making my way through Buenos Aires and on to El Calafate where our eclipse flight takes off on July 11.  This is the last total eclipse until the end of 2012 so it had better be a good one!\r\n\r\nFor more on this eclipse, visit Fred Espenak\'s dedicated NASA web page <a href=\"http://eclipse.gsfc.nasa.gov/SEmono/TSE2010/TSE2010.html\" target=\"_blank\">here.</a>\r\n\r\nCome back later in the summer to see all the new eclipse video and expedition photography.\r\n\r\nYou must see a Total Eclipse of the Sun from the air before you die!','Eclipse Chasing Again! ',0,'A lifetime of eclipse chasing continues this summer with a spectacular observation from 35,000 feet. ','inherit','open','open','','1636-revision-39','','','2010-06-11 18:20:58','2010-06-11 22:20:58','',1636,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1636-revision-39',0,'revision','',0),(1751,5,'2010-03-07 19:05:12','2010-03-07 23:05:12','','ted_news_thumb1',0,'','inherit','open','open','','ted_news_thumb1','','','2010-03-07 19:05:12','2010-03-07 23:05:12','',0,'http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/ted_news_thumb1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2247,5,'2011-01-05 20:01:12','2011-01-06 00:01:12','A partial solar eclipse pales in comparison to a total eclipse - but it is an eclipse nonetheless.  On 4 January 2011, much of Africa and Asia witnessed a partial eclipse, and observers with clear views got some great photographs.  Here is my fave!  The Sun being eclipsed by the Moon AND the International Space Station!  Astronomy rocks.  Thierry Legault shot this great image from Oman in eastern Africa.\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/partial-with-iss.jpg\" alt=\"partial-with-iss.jpg\" />\r\n\r\nThis eclipse is part of a series of eclipses called Saros 151.  There are 72 eclipses in this series - the first took place in 1776 and last one will be in 3056.  That\'s over 1280 years of eclipses - all related!  Stick around... ','Partial Solar Eclipse 4 January 2011',0,'Great shot of the partial eclipse from Oman! ','publish','open','open','','partial-solar-eclipse-4-january-2011','','','2011-01-05 20:08:00','2011-01-06 00:08:00','',0,'http://eclipseguy.dev/?p=2247',0,'post','',0),(3100,4,'2015-05-01 18:29:01','2015-05-01 22:29:01','','legsonshore1-200x130.jpg',0,'','inherit','open','open','','legsonshore1-200x130-jpg','','','2015-05-01 18:29:01','2015-05-01 22:29:01','',3099,'http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/legsonshore1-200x130.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(3101,4,'2002-07-15 17:36:28','2002-07-15 21:36:28','In June 2002, I joined eclipse chasers from around the world in Puerto Vallarta, Mexico, to observe a spectacular annular eclipse at sunset. Many of us had never met before - acquainted only by the internet. Still, hundreds of us descended on this sleepy resort town on the Pacific coast of Mexico for a few days to witness a once-in-a-lifetime event. <blockquote><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/p_hotel_01.jpg\" alt=\"puerto hotel\" />  Puerto Vallarta, Mexico</blockquote> Choosing an exact observing site for any eclipse is serious business. Each time there are different factors to consider in time and space and weather in order maximize your chances of actually seeing the thing. One little cloud can add the perfect touch or erase the sun altogether. And you never know which it is going to be until you\'re there. <blockquote><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/danielfisher.jpg\" alt=\"puerto daniel\" />  Eclipse chaser Daniel Fisher from Germany considers his options for an observation at sea.</blockquote> In the days prior to the eclipse, I teamed up with chasers Olivier \"Klipsi\" Staiger from Switzerland, and Daniel Fisher from Germany. We soon discovered that a tropical storm was brewing off the coast - right in our backyard. Satellite images confirmed that tropical storm Boris was staying put for eclipse day. Arghhh! <blockquote><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/storm.jpg\" alt=\"puerto storm\" />  Satellite image of tropical storm Boris</blockquote> This was the worst possible development! Thick clouds, wind and rain are a nightmare come true!  Nevertheless, observing sites were chosen and cameras, lenses and telescopes were packed. A hundred of some of the busiest eclipse chasers in the world, many of whom had never met before, gathered at the Hard Rock Cafe the night before to share our concerns about Boris and trade whatever secrets we had discovered. You might think that we see each other over and over again at eclipses. Sometimes we do. But with so many of us scattered around the world, and so many different locations to observe from along eclipse paths, mass gatherings of top chasers are relatively rare. It was a real pleasure to finally meet people I had known about for years.  The next day we set out in a race, in dozens of splintered expeditions, to seek the Moon\'s anti-umbra.  While many chose to drive into the path of the eclipse 50 kilometers south of Puerto Vallarta, I chose to go by sea. I had never seen an eclipse on the ocean and this was my chance to do it. <blockquote><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/serape.jpg\" alt=\"puerto serape\" />  We set out on the M.S. Sarape from Marina Terminal, Puerto Vallarta</blockquote> I joined 150 passengers, including Jay Pasachoff, the chair of the International Astronomical Union\'s Working Group on Eclipses, on the MS Serape bound for the waters off Cabo Corrientes. With tropical storm Boris still waving its ugly hand in the air, I believe we were the only organized team to attempt an observation by sea. For some it was well worth it. For others, a nightmare.  Our poor vessel had never seen such stormy seas. During our harrowing three hour journey inside the northern limit of the eclipse path, over half of our passengers became extremely sea sick, retching and vomiting beyond capacity. Then the gift shop exploded - the incessant pitching and keeling of the boat becoming too intense. The glass display cases and stands snapped into shards sending souvenirs flying as we buckled under the pressure of the waves. To make things even worse, there was water crashing in the windows on the lower deck every time we hit hard. And we weren\'t even there yet.  Still, the mayhem didn\'t stop Jay Pasachoff from presenting a great slide show about what we were hoping to see when we arrived. And I thought I had seen it all!  By the time we entered the zone of annularity, people were so sick it was only the most keen of us paying any attention to what was happening. Great beds of clouds ruled the skies with only scattered breaks where the Sun was supposed to be. I was sure we would see partial phases in part but I was wrong. Holding on for dear life and juggling a 300ml lens (which was futile) we got our only treat of the trip. A brilliant tangerine diamond burst out of the clouds - growing like a diamond ring at third contact. Then another! It was both sides of annularity! Through a break in the clouds less than a quarter of a degree wide we observed the nine and three o\'clock positions of the ring for a few seconds. Prayers went skyward for a reappearance on the horizon - but it was not meant to be. I know both Jay and I tried our best to record the event, but it was Daniel Fisher that got the best results with his video camera. The rest of us were just lucky to be alive. <blockquote><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/stormsky.jpg\" alt=\"puerto clouds\" />  The annular eclipse as seen through the clouds of tropical storm Boris. Photo Glenn Schneider</blockquote> But we all agreed that we had set a new standard in qualifying for a successful eclipse chase - the shortest observation ever!  The return journey was less rough and extremely subdued but I still had that post-eclipse glow. We dragged our soggy bottoms back into port about 11:30pm.  I consider the chase to be a complete success and one of the most outrageous of my career. I loved it! But there are many who would beg to differ and many who would do it all again.','Puerto Vallarta - 10 June 2002',0,'I have no luck with Annular Eclipses!  This was my second annular wash-out.','publish','closed','closed','','puerto-vallarta-10-june-2002','','','2002-07-15 17:36:28','2002-07-15 21:36:28','',0,'http://eclipseguy.dev/reports/puerto-vallarta-10-june-2002',0,'reports','',0),(1759,5,'2009-12-30 22:22:08','2009-12-31 02:22:08','More media attention!\r\n\r\nThis magazine is aimed at English-speaking ex-pats living in the Shanghai area. From July, 2009.\r\n<a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/shanghai_talk_magazine.pdf\">\r\nDownload the pdf here.</a>','Eclipseguy featured in Shanghai Talk Magazine',0,'Can\'t stop talking about solar eclipses! ','inherit','open','open','','1555-revision-17','','','2009-12-30 22:22:08','2009-12-31 02:22:08','',1555,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1555-revision-17',0,'revision','',0),(1761,5,'2010-09-01 19:23:58','2010-09-01 23:23:58','Follow the handy-work of famous Canadian eclipse chaser Andreas Gada as he opens the iris on the Total Eclipse of 1980 in Voi, Kenya. This is some of the only 16mm eclipse film you will ever see! Killer!','16mm Eclipse film from 1980',0,'More sweet 16mm film from 1980!','inherit','open','open','','608-autosave','','','2010-09-01 19:23:58','2010-09-01 23:23:58','',608,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/608-autosave',0,'revision','',0),(1762,5,'2009-05-22 22:45:27','2009-05-23 02:45:27','Follow the handy-work of famous Canadian eclipse chaser Andreas Gada as he opens the iris on the Total Eclipse of 1979 in Gimli, Manitoba. This is some of the only 16mm eclipse film you will ever see! Killer!','16mm Eclipse film from 1979',0,'More sweet 16mm film from 1979!','inherit','open','open','','608-revision-8','','','2009-05-22 22:45:27','2009-05-23 02:45:27','',608,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/608-revision-8',0,'revision','',0),(1763,5,'2010-04-09 18:06:09','2010-04-09 22:06:09','Follow the handy-work of famous Canadian eclipse chaser Andreas Gada as he opens the iris on the Total Eclipse of 1980 in Voi, Kenya. This is some of the only 16mm eclipse film you will ever see! Killer!','16mm Eclipse film from 1980',0,'More sweet 16mm film from 1979!','inherit','open','open','','608-revision-9','','','2010-04-09 18:06:09','2010-04-09 22:06:09','',608,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/608-revision-9',0,'revision','',0),(1764,5,'2010-02-11 10:22:14','2010-02-11 14:22:14','On 11 July 2010, a Total Solar Eclipse will be visible from a long corridor that spans the southern Pacific Ocean.  Tahiti will be teeming with eclipse seekers and adventurers taking to the sea in cruise liners and boarding flights to remote Tuamotu Islands.  Easter Island will also be packed to its shores with human eyes looking skyward.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Animation of the Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2010jul11t.gif\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">THIS SEAT HAS BEEN TAKEN!  THANK YOU! </span>\r\n\r\nBut at the end of the eclipse day, the Moon\'s shadow crosses extreme southern Chile where an organization called Eclipse-City will operate a private charter to fly into the path of the eclipse in mid air and intercept the shadow at  35, 000 feet.  I have two rows booked on this flight.  Each row has two people sharing the window where the eclipse will be visible above Earth\'s western horizon.  As of 15 January 2010, I have one seat available in the row where the plane\'s wing will be visible.  The wing creates no blind spot for the eclipse itself, but obviously removes a portion of the sky from view.  These are the least expensive seats on the aircraft, with the \"no wing\" seats costing the most.  <del datetime=\"2010-02-11T14:19:04+00:00\">This seat is available now for €499/USD715.</del> If you are interested, post a comment here or contact me by email.  This seat will not be available for long!\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.eclipse-city.com/eclipse,patagonia,10087.html\" target=\"_blank\">Eclipse City</a>\r\n<a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/091218_observation-flight.pdf\">Download Seating Plan</a>\r\n\r\nYou have to get yourself to El Calafate, Argentina, by 11 July 2010.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path.jpg\"></a><a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path2.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1716 aligncenter\" title=\"Microsoft Word - July 2009 Patagonia English\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path2.jpg\" alt=\"Microsoft Word - July 2009 Patagonia English\" width=\"450\" height=\"375\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\nWith South Pacific cruises either cost-prohibitive or completely sold out, and Easter Island already packed to the rafters, this is definitely the most exciting and cost-effective option left.  And you don\'t have to worry about the weather!  This flight will travel well above any threatening clouds and we are guaranteed a spectacular observation in crystal clear skies. We will see approximately 2:55 of Totality.\r\n\r\nYou must see a Total Eclipse of the Sun from the air before you die!','ONE SEAT AVAILABLE! Eclipse Observation Flight/Patagonia/July 2010.',0,'I have one seat available on an exclusive eclipse observation flight from Patagonia, 11 July 2010.  Come see an eclipse with me!  Goes to the first caller!  ','inherit','open','open','','1636-revision-35','','','2010-02-11 10:22:14','2010-02-11 14:22:14','',1636,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1636-revision-35',0,'revision','',0),(1765,5,'2010-04-17 19:27:31','2010-04-17 23:27:31','','se2012may20a',0,'','inherit','open','open','','se2012may20a','','','2010-04-17 19:27:31','2010-04-17 23:27:31','',551,'http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2012may20a.gif',0,'attachment','image/gif',0),(1766,5,'2010-04-17 19:33:05','2010-04-17 23:33:05','','se2012nov13t',0,'','inherit','open','open','','se2012nov13t','','','2010-04-17 19:33:05','2010-04-17 23:33:05','',551,'http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2012nov13t.gif',0,'attachment','image/gif',0),(1767,5,'2010-04-17 19:41:10','2010-04-17 23:41:10','','se2013may10a',0,'','inherit','open','open','','se2013may10a','','','2010-04-17 19:41:10','2010-04-17 23:41:10','',551,'http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2013may10a.gif',0,'attachment','image/gif',0),(1772,5,'2010-06-11 18:15:53','2010-06-11 22:15:53','On 11 July 2010, a Total Solar Eclipse will be visible from a long corridor that spans the southern Pacific Ocean.  Tahiti will be teeming with eclipse seekers and adventurers taking to the sea in cruise liners and boarding flights to remote Tuamotu Islands.  Easter Island will also be packed to its shores with human eyes looking skyward.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Animation of the Total Solar Eclipse of 11 July 2010</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/se2010jul11t.gif\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n\r\nBut at the end of the eclipse day, the Moon\'s shadow crosses extreme southern Chile/Argentina where an organization called Eclipse-City will operate a private charter to fly into the path of the eclipse in mid air and intercept the shadow at  35, 000 feet.  This is where I will be!  It\'s my first observation from an aircraft!  Miles above the clouds, we are guaranteed a perfect view!  From this unique vantage point, we will see approximately 3:50 of Totality.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path.jpg\"></a><a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path2.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1716 aligncenter\" title=\"Microsoft Word - July 2009 Patagonia English\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/2010_eclipse_flight_path2.jpg\" alt=\"Microsoft Word - July 2009 Patagonia English\" width=\"450\" height=\"375\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\nIn the weeks prior to the eclipse, I will be visiting Peru for the first time.  I land in Lima - visit Puno - Lake Titicaca - then take the train through the Andes to Cuzco where I will embark on the famous Inca Trail hike up to Machu Picchu.  This spectacular trek takes three days and is one of the most intense hikes of my eclipse chasing career!  Amazing!  Then it\'s back to Lima before making my way through Buenos Aires and on to El Calafate where our eclipse flight takes off on July 11.  This is the last total eclipse until the end of 2012 so it had better be a good one!\r\n\r\nCome back later in the summer to see all the new eclipse video and expedition photography.\r\n\r\nYou must see a Total Eclipse of the Sun from the air before you die!','Eclipse Chasing Again! ',0,'A lifetime of eclipse chasing continues this summer with a spectacular observation from 35,000 feet. ','inherit','open','open','','1636-revision-37','','','2010-06-11 18:15:53','2010-06-11 22:15:53','',1636,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1636-revision-37',0,'revision','',0),(1743,5,'2010-02-26 17:46:05','2010-02-26 21:46:05','<h2>Hooked On The Shadow</h2>\r\nThis is my documentary film about the sub-culture of eclipse chasers. It originally aired in Canada on Space, has screened at film festivals, won awards, and for the last 10 years has been utilized by tour operators and astronomy groups to introduce audiences to the world of eclipse chasing. To commemorate the 12th anniversary of the Caribbean eclipse of 26 February 1998 - where I began filming this documentary - I am very pleased to finally make the film available to everyone as a free download for the first time. Enjoy!\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/video/hooked-on-the-shadow-2\">Watch</a> the film in the Video Vault.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://vimeo.com/3246075\" target=\"_blank\">Download</a> the complete film at Vimeo!','Complete Film Free Download',0,'See my award winning film Hooked On The Shadow in its entirety on the web for the first time, or download the complete film from Vimeo. ','publish','open','open','','complete-film-free-download','','\nhttp://eclipseguy.dev/video/hooked-on-the-shadow-2','2010-02-28 11:35:31','2010-02-28 15:35:31','',0,'http://eclipseguy.dev/?p=1743',0,'post','',0),(1744,5,'2010-02-27 17:43:19','2010-02-27 21:43:19','','hots_full_thumb',0,'','inherit','open','open','','hots_full_thumb','','','2010-02-27 17:43:19','2010-02-27 21:43:19','',1743,'http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/hots_full_thumb.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1745,5,'2010-02-27 17:45:33','2010-02-27 21:45:33','This is my documentary film about the sub-culture of eclipse chasers. It originally aired in Canada on Space, has screened at film festivals, won awards, and for the last 10 years has been utilized by tour operators and astronomy gro