eguy.dev/uncategorized/971-revision-2',0,'revision','',0),(1033,5,'2009-05-22 20:26:59','2009-05-23 00:26:59','While most cameras are pointed at the sky during a Total Eclipse, the best way to get a sense of what it feels like to be there is to witness what is happening to the people on the ground. In this clip, watch as the Moon\'s shadow arrives, then retreats, from our observing spot - an ancient archeological site 1,000 feet above the Tigris River in Southern Turkey. So killer!','Darkness in Turkey 1999',0,'One of the best ways to get a sense of a Total Eclipse is not to watch the sky... but watch the people on the ground! Daytime turns into night before your eyes!','inherit','open','open','','967-revision-2','','','2009-05-22 20:26:59','2009-05-23 00:26:59','',967,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/967-revision-2',0,'revision','',0),(1034,5,'2009-05-22 20:17:04','2009-05-23 00:17:04','During the eclipse expedition to China in 2008, we passed through the city of Xi\'an and had the chance to see the famous Terracotta Warriors. More than 8,000 warriors, horses and chariots have been uncovered.  They were created in 246 BC but not discovered until 1974. My invitation into the private area in the facility to film the warriors that are being repaired allowed me to get amazing, close up pictures of these sculptures.  ','The Terracotta Warriors',0,'The magnificent Terracotta Warriors!  Unique, behind-the-scenes footage - rarely seen like this. ','inherit','open','open','','958-revision-6','','','2009-05-22 20:17:04','2009-05-23 00:17:04','',958,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/958-revision-6',0,'revision','',0),(1036,5,'2009-04-20 19:23:49','2009-04-20 23:23:49','In the Australian Outback in 2002, the Total Eclipse happened just before sunset. When the Sun hit the western horizon, the Moon was still in the way! This was a once-in-a-lifetime experience. Check it ou',' Eclipsed Sun Sets!',0,'Watch an eclipsed sun set! ','inherit','open','open','','658-revision-3','','','2009-04-20 19:23:49','2009-04-20 23:23:49','',658,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/658-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(1037,5,'2009-04-20 19:20:51','2009-04-20 23:20:51','In this clip from the Total Eclipse of December 2002 in the Outback, I have modified the speed and contrast in order to accentuate the movement of the Moon\'s shadow across the Earth. You don\'t get to see the Moon\'s umbra move like this everyday!',' Shadowdance',0,'Killer animation of the Moon\'s shadow sweeping through the sky! ','inherit','open','open','','654-revision-3','','','2009-04-20 19:20:51','2009-04-20 23:20:51','',654,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/654-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(1038,5,'2009-04-20 19:16:01','2009-04-20 23:16:01','The \"Diamond Ring\" phase of a Total Eclipse signals the beginning of totality, and the end of totality. You get two Diamond Rings every eclipse! Watch both in this clip from the Total Eclipse in Zambia, Africa in 2001.','Africa Diamonds',0,'Watch two Diamond Rings in Zambia, Africa in 2001.','inherit','open','open','','649-revision-3','','','2009-04-20 19:16:01','2009-04-20 23:16:01','',649,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/649-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(1039,5,'2009-04-20 19:10:49','2009-04-20 23:10:49','Follow the handy-work of famous Canadian eclipse chaser Andreas Gada as he opens the iris on the Total Eclipse of 1979 in Gimli, Manitoba. This is some of the only 16mm eclipse film you will ever see! Killer!','16mm Eclipse film from 1979',0,'More sweet 16mm film from 1979!','inherit','open','open','','608-revision-7','','','2009-04-20 19:10:49','2009-04-20 23:10:49','',608,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/608-revision-7',0,'revision','',0),(1040,5,'2009-04-20 19:04:01','2009-04-20 23:04:01','In this fast-motion, wide-angle shot of the eclipse in Yiwu, China, in 2008, we can clearly see the shadow of the Moon sweep across the Earth towards us - bathe us in its unearthly light - then sweep away from us at over 3000 kilometers per hour. You rarely get to see umbral action like this! Spine-tingling!','Umbral Action!',0,'Watch the umbra move across Earth! ','inherit','open','open','','635-revision-3','','','2009-04-20 19:04:01','2009-04-20 23:04:01','',635,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/635-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(1041,5,'2009-04-20 19:00:53','2009-04-20 23:00:53','Eclipse in China - 01 August 2008. This is only a preview of the complete film which I have not finished yet! But the eclipse sequence is so dramatic I want to share it now. The clouds that threatened to eclipse the eclipse actually provided an ideal platform under which to observe the full motion of the umbra through the sky. Stunning! Don\'t miss the time-lapse version of this shot as well, \"Umbral Action.\"','Shadow On The Silk Road',0,'Amazing eclipse action in China!','inherit','open','open','','631-revision-3','','','2009-04-20 19:00:53','2009-04-20 23:00:53','',631,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/631-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(1042,5,'2009-04-19 19:45:55','2009-04-19 23:45:55','My friend Jim Huddle shot this amazing footage of the Total Eclipse in Antarctica in November 2003. From his location, the eclipse happened right on the horizon making this eclipse unique in the experience of eclipse chasers. I was in Antarctica as well for this one, but at a different location. Together, we were among the first humans to witness a Total Eclipse from Antarctica.','Antarctica Total Eclipse 2003',0,'It looks fake but this is real!!!!  Totality in Antarctica.  ','inherit','open','open','','618-revision-3','','','2009-04-19 19:45:55','2009-04-19 23:45:55','',618,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/618-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(1043,5,'2009-04-19 19:17:21','2009-04-19 23:17:21','Watch the change in light on the beach as the Moon\'s shadow departs our location at Baby Beach in Aruba in 1998.','The Umbra Retreats in Aruba',0,'Watch the Umbra retreat in Aruba in 1998.','inherit','open','open','','614-revision-3','','','2009-04-19 19:17:21','2009-04-19 23:17:21','',614,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/614-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(1044,5,'2009-04-20 19:05:45','2009-04-20 23:05:45','The Total Eclipse of 1991 over Hawaii, Mexico and Central America was considered \"The Big One\" because the duration of totality was one of the longest of the 20th century. This eclipse is also considered to be the one that launched the modern day phenomenon known as \"eclipse chasing\" when in fact people have been flocking to see Total Solar Eclipses for centuries. Famous Canadian eclipse photographer Andreas Gada shot this 16mm film from Baja California. It don\'t get no betta!!! Sweeeet!!!','The Big One 1991',0,'Sweet 16mm eclipse film from The Big One!','inherit','open','open','','604-revision-4','','','2009-04-20 19:05:45','2009-04-20 23:05:45','',604,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/604-revision-4',0,'revision','',0),(1045,5,'2009-04-20 19:09:44','2009-04-20 23:09:44','Thanks to NASA\'s public service, these images of the Total Eclipse from Turkey in 1999 show great chromosphere and a few stunning moments of the inner corona.Â  Check it out!Â  No audio on this one.','Totality in Turkey 1999',0,'Great shots of the corona courtesy of NASA! ','inherit','open','open','','600-revision-4','','','2009-04-20 19:09:44','2009-04-20 23:09:44','',600,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/600-revision-4',0,'revision','',0),(1046,5,'2009-04-20 19:08:16','2009-04-20 23:08:16','Watch me on the news in South Australia talking        about the Moon\'s shadow over Lyndhurst on December 4, 2002.','Eclipseguy in the news in Australia!',0,'Catch me on the news in Australia! ','inherit','open','open','','595-revision-5','','','2009-04-20 19:08:16','2009-04-20 23:08:16','',595,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/595-revision-5',0,'revision','',0),(3105,4,'2010-08-01 20:52:48','2010-08-02 00:52:48','<blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">My 17th Solar Eclipse Expedition</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">My 12th successfully-observed Total Eclipse in a Row<img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/dm_picchu_600_02.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">On the way to Patagonia, I spent two weeks in Peru.  The classic Machu Picchu shot!</p> </blockquote> <p class=\"MsoNormal\">I don’t think anyone would argue with me if I said that eclipse chasers really want to see the eclipse.<span> </span>But can we anthropomorphize the eclipse and say, <em>it</em> really wants to be seen?<span> </span></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\">The TSE of 11 July 2010 was visible from Tahiti and the surrounding islands – across Easter Island through the south Pacific – ending on the very tip of South America - in Patagonia.<span> </span>Eighteen months before the eclipse, I was booked on a small clipper ship out of Tahiti – we were going to sail the remote Tuamotu Islands of French Polynesia for a week – then see the eclipse in the ocean off Tahiti’s south coast.<span> </span>The perfect plan.<span> </span>I was totally pumped.<span> </span>The idea of sailing around these islands en route to totality was a life dream come true.<span> </span>I love trains.<span> </span>And I love sail boats.</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/TSE2010globe_rev_500.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\">But no sail ever happened!<span> </span>They cancelled it months in advance.<span> </span>Apparently, the ship operator decided to redeploy the vessel to other, richer waters and dumped 75 chasers from the manifest.<span> </span>Nice.</p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\">I was then without an eclipse plan.<span> </span>And I let it slide.<span> </span>For months.<span> </span>Pretty soon, all the other Tahiti cruises were sold out.<span> </span>I checked into the tours and the music festival happening on Easter Island – loved the sound of it – but too expensive.<span> </span>(The greed of the tour operators and the airlines early in the selling turned away many people, and in the final few weeks before the eclipse they couldn’t give away their seats. The throngs of people that were supposed to show up on Rapa Nui for this eclipse never materialized).<span> </span>So I booked the next best option – a reasonably priced eclipse flight – a private charter into the path of the eclipse at 35,000 ft.<span> </span>A guaranteed cloudless eclipse!<span> </span>We couldn’t miss!<span> </span>So I booked passage to El Calafate – a sleepy cottage town in Patagonia – where the flight would take off on 11 July 2010.<span> </span></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\">But two days before the eclipse – they cancelled the flight.<span> </span>Problems with the aircraft, we were told.<span> </span>I was halfway around the world already and feared I would miss my first Total Eclipse in 20 years.<span> </span></p> <p class=\"MsoNormal\">But against all odds, the eclipse was seen in a pristine sky above the Andes Mountains.<span> </span>This was the eclipse that wouldn’t take no for an answer.<span> </span></p> <p><!--nextpage--></p> <p>And in keeping with my desire to see the whole world while eclipse chasing, I took advantage of the opportunity and booked two weeks in Peru before the eclipse.  Lima - Puno - Cuzco - the Inca Trail - Machu Picchu.  Classic Peru.</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/worldmap_peru.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p>The big attraction for me in Peru was the Inca Trail - the famous 4-day hike through the Andes Mountains to the city of Machu Picchu.  I had wanted to do this journey since I was old enough to read.</p> <p>Entering Peru through the city of Lima, I move straight to Puno.  At 12,500 feet, Puno is one of the highest places on the continent and it\'s famous because this is where you go to visit Lake Titicaca - the world\'s highest navigable lake and a critical location in the Inca heritage.</p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4767.jpg\" alt=\"puno\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The city of Puno.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4701.jpg\" alt=\"puno\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">It takes me two days to get over the symptoms of High Altitude Sickness.</p> </blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: left;\">I head out on to Lake Titicaca and visit the floating islands of Uros - where a traditional culture lives on man-made islands, fashioned from the endless supply of reeds growing in the lake.</p> <p style=\"text-align: left;\"> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4724.jpg\" alt=\"uros village\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">It floats!  Islands of Uros in Lake Titicaca.</p> </blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4722.jpg\" alt=\"uros reeds\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Imagine your house - your floor - your bed - all made out of this.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4727.jpg\" alt=\"uros boat\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Boats too!</p> </blockquote> <p><!--nextpage--></p> <p style=\"text-align: left;\"> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4751.jpg\" alt=\"taquile island\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Agricultural terraces on Taquile.</p> </blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: left;\">The island of Taquile is three hours away by boat.  This remote Quechua  outpost still lives by the traditional Inca values of community  collectivism.  The island is gorgeous - lush - small farms -  agricultural terraces - but the hike to the public square at over 4,000  meters above sea level takes the wind out of me.  Until you have adapted  to the altitude, you can\'t draw a full breath - and walking uphill is slow and difficult for me.</p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4738.jpg\" alt=\"taquile wheat\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Fields of wheat.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4745.jpg\" alt=\"taquile coca\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Fresh coca leaves can be purchased as easily as a bag of chips.  Helps with the Altitude Sickness...!</p> </blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4748.jpg\" alt=\"taquile arch\" /></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4753.jpg\" alt=\"taquile steps\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The way down is much easier!</p> </blockquote> <p><!--nextpage--></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4844.jpg\" alt=\"train start\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">I love trains!</p> </blockquote> <p>The romance of long distance travel by train must be archetypal because I have fallen prey to its influence my entire life.  This one was a real treat - best train journey ever!  I leave Puno - travel through the Peruvian Altiplano and into the Andes that surround Cuzco - my destination.  The ride takes all day - over 10 hours.  En route I witness the most incredible sights - all part of a sparse but vibrant high altitude culture - thriving in the most remote of regions.</p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4823.jpg\" alt=\"train village\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Ancient mountain villages.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4791.jpg\" alt=\"train market\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">As the train passes through, we split the market in two. Inches from the stalls!</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4786.jpg\" alt=\"train market 2\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Seconds after we pass, the market swallows up the tracks once again.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4795.jpg\" alt=\"train parts\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Spare parts for your train, sir?</p> </blockquote> <p><!--nextpage--></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4782.jpg\" alt=\"train interior\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">First Class.  Isn\'t it the only way?  And I was one of only 4 people on the train!</p> </blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4849.jpg\" alt=\"train dm\" /></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4812.jpg\" alt=\"train sussut\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The Observation Car.  Where I spent most of my time.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4826.jpg\" alt=\"train vista\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">At over 4,300 meters, the peak at La Raya is the highest point on our journey. I felt really lucky to be seeing all this.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4857.jpg\" alt=\"train shadows\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Postcard anyone?</p> </blockquote> <p><!--nextpage--></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4885.jpg\" alt=\"train postcard\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Shall we make it two?  One of my faves.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4830.jpg\" alt=\"train woman\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">A baby alpaca in the arms of its... mother!  The alpaca wool trade is critical to the Peruvian economy.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4845.jpg\" alt=\"train end\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">I love trains.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5008.jpg\" alt=\"cuzco wide\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Cuzco.  The Imperial City of the Incas.</p> </blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: left;\">Cuzco is an incredibly busy place.  One gets the sense that it has always been.  As the starting point for hikers on the Inca Trail, it is constantly flooded with backpackers and tourists making their way through town.  But this tourism hasn\'t pushed the locals away.  As I move around - shoulder to shoulder with the crowds - I pass as many moms with newborns as uniformed school kids as local cart merchants.  There is probably a young hiker couple here from every city in Europe!</p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4976.jpg\" alt=\"cuzco city\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The rainbow flag is the official symbol of Cuzco.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4937.jpg\" alt=\"cuzco cathedral\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Cathedral at the town square.</p> </blockquote> <p><!--nextpage--></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4958.jpg\" alt=\"cuzco market\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Hands down Cuzco has the best markets in Peru.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4954.jpg\" alt=\"cuzco textile\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">If you can\'t stand vibrant colors, endless variety - stay clear!</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4985.jpg\" alt=\"cuzco sun temple\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">What\'s left of the mind-blowing Inca Temple of the Sun or Qorikancha after the Spanish ruined everything.   It is here I begin my wonder with all things Inca.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_4988.jpg\" alt=\"cuzco trapezoid\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Inca engineering:  trapezoid windows and doorways.  Aligned, of course.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5000.jpg\" alt=\"cuzco ruins\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The monumental complex of Saqsaywaman, north of Cuzco city.  Meticulously formed boulders put together without mortar.  The Incas were a crafty bunch.</p> </blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: left;\"> <p><!--nextpage--></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5054.jpg\" alt=\"sacred valley\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The Sacred Valley.</p> </blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: left;\">After a nerve-racking night of trying to pack smartly for my 4-day hike/camp along the Inca Trail (never take more than 5kg!), I make my way through the storied Sacred Valley.  Like something from a history book, this whole region is at once stunning to the eye and overwhelming to the heart.  I stop at several noteworthy sites along the way including Pisac - known for its great Sunday markets.</p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5087.jpg\" alt=\"pisac walls\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The village of Pisac in the Sacred Valley.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5072.jpg\" alt=\"pisac market\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Part of Pisac\'s extensive markets.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5116.jpg\" alt=\"chapel\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">I came across this chapel with incredible natural light.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5131.jpg\" alt=\"ollantaytambo\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">I overnight in Ollantaytambo before heading out on foot on the Inca Trail.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5144.jpg\" alt=\"ollantaytambo street\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Streets of Ollantaytambo.  The emperor Pachacuti made this town his home. But that was a long time ago.</p> </blockquote> <p><!--nextpage--></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5158.jpg\" alt=\"trail start\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Finally!  The start of the great Inca Trail!  I have been waiting for this a long time.  This point is called Kilometer 82.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5163.jpg\" alt=\"inca valley\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Stunning sights await all on this ancient pilgrimage.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5238.jpg\" alt=\"trail path\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Most of what you are walking on is this - rocks and boulders that stretch out for over 40km.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5204.jpg\" alt=\"trail vista 1\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">I frequently have to stop and pinch myself.  Nope.  Not dreaming.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5165.jpg\" alt=\"trail ruins 1\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Amazingly well-preserved agricultural terraces litter this area of the Andes.  A peak into what life was like - long ago.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5218.jpg\" alt=\"trail up \" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The 4-day hike is extremely challenging in places - and not for the timid.  Completely dizzying.</p> </blockquote> <p><!--nextpage--></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5194.jpg\" alt=\"trail manuel\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">My private guide, Manuel, spent 5 years on the road to being a Catholic priest.  Eventually, the spirituality of the Incas, his true ancestors, resonated on a much deeper level and he has been a guide for over 10 years.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5177.jpg\" alt=\"trail gear\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">This is what your gear looks like.  Private porters carry the bulk of it - I carried a single knapsack only. That\'s enough for this terrain!</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5211.jpg\" alt=\"trail sellers\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The occasional rest-stop offers hikers the essentials - at a premium.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5175.jpg\" alt=\"trail camp 1\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Our porters setting us up for the night.  The sun set around 6pm each night.  I was crashed by 9pm - latest.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5212.jpg\" alt=\"trail coca\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The real thing.</p> </blockquote> <p>The coca leaf is revered throughout Peruvian culture for its magical and medicinal qualities.  The lift in spirit and energy that chewing on a few leaves can bring was a most welcome effect in these mountains!  I learned to love it as my Peruvian friends did.  Brought some home, too!  (Shhh.)</p> <p><!--nextpage--></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5225.jpg\" alt=\"trail vista 2\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Imagine waking up to this!  Nice to look at - harder to conquer.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5224.jpg\" alt=\"trail peak\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Winded hikers make the final few steps to Dead Woman\'s Pass after 5 hours of straight, uphill trekking.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5234.jpg\" alt=\"trail top\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Dead Woman\'s Pass.  This is the tail end of Day 2.  From here to Machu Picchu, the trail descends almost 2,000 meters in altitude.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5292.jpg\" alt=\"trail vista 2\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The stunning beauty of this trail can not be overstated.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5370.jpg\" alt=\"trail drop off\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">It is also dangerous.  If you misstep - it means certain death.  The trail is very uneven and less than a meter wide here.</p> </blockquote> <p><!--nextpage--></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5537.jpg\" alt=\"trail sussut walks\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The Incas were hard core.  One is meant to be changed by this approach to Machu Picchu city.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5437.jpg\" alt=\"trail terraces wide\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Inca ruins and agricultural terraces - like this one - can be found daily along the trail.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5271.jpg\" alt=\"trail ruins \" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The chambers, walls &amp; entrances are all aligned with the sky in some way.  Earth\'s journey around the sun every year was critical to the identity the Incas created for themselves.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5317A.jpg\" alt=\"trail ruins cu\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">I was amazed how we were allowed to explore in intimate detail all the ruins we encountered.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5356.jpg\" alt=\"trail lunch \" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Hikes along the trail are pro all the way.  Your stops are predetermined each day.  Porters are ahead of you - lunch is always ready!  This was the best food of the entire trip.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5447.jpg\" alt=\"trail dark mountains\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">By the end of Day 3 - I am hiking way high in the Andes.</p> </blockquote> <p><!--nextpage--></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5411.jpg\" alt=\"trail sussut points\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Am I actually getting used to sights like these?</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5413.jpg\" alt=\"trail camp 2\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">We camped here on Day 3.  And I don\'t even like heights!  I was dizzy the whole time.  Yes - it is straight down beyond that little tree.  Did we bring a flashlight?</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5422.jpg\" alt=\"trail camp 2A\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">As the sun set and the fog rolled in, it was obvious:  we were camped in heaven.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5454.jpg\" alt=\"trail vista 3\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Day 4 served up some of the most terrifying parts of the trail.  I actually trembled a few times. That\'s the Urubamba River.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5514.jpg\" alt=\"machu picchu 1\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">By noon on Day 4, the city of Machu Picchu appears out of the highland jungle.  It is everything you think it is going to be - and then more.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5486.jpg\" alt=\"dm &amp; sussut sungate\" /><br /> Me and my excellent hiker pal Sue at the Sun Gate overlooking Machu Picchu city.</p></blockquote> <p><!--nextpage--></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5584.jpg\" alt=\"machu picchu 2\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Built by Andean masons in the 1400s, it was unknown to the outside world until 1911.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5653.jpg\" alt=\"machu picchu 3\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">There is a quiet fascination exploring Machu Picchu.  With its massive scale and soaring spirit, it is simply extraordinary.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5588.jpg\" alt=\"mach\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The city is brilliantly conceived with agricultural zones - residential areas - observatories - royal enclosures and temples. Seems like they knew something we don\'t.</p> </blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5599.jpg\" alt=\"machu picchu 5\" /></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5600.jpg\" alt=\"machu picchu 6\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">I\'d give anything to be here on the solstice on the 21st of June!</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5523.jpg\" alt=\"aguas callientes\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Aguas Calientes</p> </blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: left;\">After the grueling trial of the trail, we final get to relax (and shower!) in Aguas Calientes - the hot springs town at the base of Machu Picchu mountain. This is where I check my email after many days - only to discover my eclipse flight has been canceled.  You\'re lucky you weren\'t around when I got this news.</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><!--nextpage--><br /> <img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/world_map_buenos.jpg\" alt=\"worldmap buenos\" /><br /> What you don\'t see now is the long journey back to Cuzco - the flight to Lima - the flight down to Buenos Aires - the 10-hour layover in the airport - then the flight to El Calafate in Patagonia at the bottom of Argentina.  I am furious at my eclipse tour company the whole time and not fun to travel with.  If there is no flight - then I am stuck on the ground - and the weather is supposed to be overcast in Calafate - hence the plane idea.  Take my eclipse away from me and watch out.  To make matters worse, we are greeted at the airport by minus 20 degree temperatures and thick ice on the ground.  It was bleak.  With no eclipse on the horizon - what the hell am I doing here?</p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5675.jpg\" alt=\"el calafate\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">El Calafate in Patagonia the morning of the eclipse.  Is that clear sky I see...?</p> </blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: left;\">Against all good sense, the tour company asks me to pay if I want to come see the eclipse from their ground location.  After leaving me with no flight!  But it\'s eclipse day already - I am out of options.  I pay.  But I could have strangled them.  I now have just a glimmer of hope that these clear skies will hold out.  That\'s my focus.  About 150 of us load into these wicked 4x4 trekking machines to haul us up to the top of the Patagonian steppe.  If we stay down in Calafate - the eclipse will set behind the mountains before we can see it.  If this eclipse really does want to be seen - it\'s down to this machine -</p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5677.jpg\" alt=\"trekker 4x4\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Couldn\'t stand the tour company.  Loved the ride to the top.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/51_chains.jpg\" alt=\"tire chains\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">As we enter the roughest part of the journey, chains are strapped on to the tires to keep us moving forward through the snow and ice.  Photo: Lukas G.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/55_trekker.jpg\" alt=\"trekker action\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Rough but awesome!  Wait... wasn\'t I just in Machu Picchu??   Photo: Lukas G.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5700.jpg\" alt=\"trekker 4x4 others\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">At least they seem to know what they\'re doing on the ground.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5686.jpg\" alt=\"eclipse site\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">What you can\'t see is the temperature!  Freezing!  Windy as hell!  The tents make it workable.</p> </blockquote> <p><!--nextpage--></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5705.jpg\" alt=\"chasers\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The partial phase of the eclipse has begun.  Barely a cloud in the sky.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5698.jpg\" alt=\"chasers 1\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Chasers having fun with safe solar viewing!</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5707.jpg\" alt=\"chasers 2\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Stunning location for an eclipse?  I think so.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5712.jpg\" alt=\"dm at eclipse\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Only 4 minutes before the eclipse do I concede:  we\'re going to see this thing after all!</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/IMG_5719.jpg\" alt=\"pre eclipse vista\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">The scene over the Andes - seconds before the shadow of the Moon arrives.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/wide_500.jpg\" alt=\"totality wide\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Embrace of the Shadow.  Lukas G. captures this amazing image of the shadow cone seemingly reaching out from beyond the mountains.</p> </blockquote> <p><!--nextpage--></p> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/totality_600.jpg\" alt=\"totality el calafate\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Hovering over the Andes in the distance  -  this is the lowest eclipse I have ever seen.  And a golden corona!  Another first!</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/diamond_600.jpg\" alt=\"diamond el calafate\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">It lasts 2:40 - but feels like 10 seconds.  The Diamond Ring at 3rd contact.</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/shadow_sky.jpg\" alt=\"shadow in sky\" /></p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">Seconds later we see the sky cut in half by the umbra.  Total Eclipse to the right; no Total Eclipse to the left.</p> </blockquote> <p style=\"text-align: left;\"> <p style=\"text-align: left;\">Success sure is sweet!  But I could have done without all the drama in the last few days.  But that is what eclipse chasers deal with.  I would do it all again.  This really was the eclipse that wouldn\'t take no for an answer.</p> <p style=\"text-align: left;\">Wanna come next time?</p> <p style=\"text-align: left;\">','South America - 11 July 2010',0,'The eclipse in Patagonia 