se day.  Across eastern China, thousands of chasers pulled all-nighters and bit their nails down to the skin watching the satellite images cast doom and gloom on our hopes of clear skies.  Just hours before the eclipse began, I decided there was no clear advantage to running, and we stayed at Naked Retreats in Moganshan to try our luck.  And while Shanghai was drenched with rain, and other \"best sites\" were completely clouded out, we experienced one of the most dramatic eclipses of the last 20 years.  Through blankets of rolling mist and fog we caught multiple glimpses of totality through holes in the sky.  The video is awesome!  Just goes to show that while clear skies is what you hope for, nature will always surprize you with its wonders.  Not what I was expecting - but completely satisfied.\r\n\r\nWatch the new video!\r\n\r\nAnd while I prepare my FULL report, check out these links:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/krisdelcourte/sets/72157621822513677/show/\" target=\"_blank\">Mr. Black Sun</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.boston.com/bigpicture/2009/07/the_longest_solar_eclipse_of_t.html\" target=\"_blank\">The Boston Globe</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://s10.photobucket.com/albums/a120/alsonwong/China%202009/?action=view&amp;current=DSC_0002Crop800.jpg\" target=\"_blank\">Alson Wong Images</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://spaceweather.com/eclipses/gallery_22jul09.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Space Weather</a>','The Misty Eclipse!  ',0,'Through blankets of rolling mist and fog we witnessed the grand Total Eclipse of 2009. Read the preliminary report.  NEW VIDEO!!!','inherit','open','open','','1509-revision-24','','','2010-06-12 18:42:33','2010-06-12 22:42:33','',1509,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1509-revision-24',0,'revision','',0),(2126,5,'2009-08-03 08:55:09','2009-08-03 12:55:09','<img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/solar_eclipse_animate_2009-jul-22.gif\" />\r\n\r\nIf you were standing out in space on eclipse day - 22 July 2009 -  this is how the Total Eclipse would have looked!  That tiny black dot moving across the Earth is the only place you could see the Total Eclipse.  If you were anywhere in the broader, outer shadow - the penumbra - you would have seen a partial eclipse only.  ','2009 Solar Eclipse Animation ',0,'See how July\'s Total Eclipse moved across the Earth. ','inherit','open','open','','1478-revision-19','','','2009-08-03 08:55:09','2009-08-03 12:55:09','',1478,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/1478-revision-19',0,'revision','',0),(2127,5,'2010-08-29 22:04:02','2010-08-30 02:04:02','<h2 style=\"text-align: left;\"><span style=\"color: #ff9900;\"><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Solar Eclipse Expeditions</span></span></h2>\r\nHere is the accounting of my adventures into the Moon\'s shadow over the last 20 years.  You get the date, the place, the eclipse type and duration observed. Available Trip Reports are linked in blue.\r\n<h4><span style=\"color: #ffcc99;\"><span style=\"color: #ffcc99;\">11 Jul 1991</span> </span>- <a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/tripreport/total-solar-eclipse-11-july-1991-mexico\">La Paz, Mexico</a> - Total - 6:50</h4>\r\n<h4><strong><span style=\"color: #ffcc99;\">04 Jan 1992 </span>- Catalina Island, USA - Annular - not seen </strong></h4>\r\n<h4><strong><span style=\"color: #ffcc99;\">10 May 1994</span> - Stratford, Canada - Annular - </strong>5:39</h4>\r\n<h4><strong><span style=\"color: #ffcc99;\">03 Nov 1994</span> - <a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/tripreport/brazil-03-november-1994\">Iguazu Falls, Brazil </a>- Total - 3:39</strong></h4>\r\n<h4><strong><span style=\"color: #ffcc99;\">24 Oct 1995</span> - <a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/tripreport/india-24-october-1995\">Fatehpur Sikri, India </a>- Total -  0:59</strong></h4>\r\n<h4><strong><span style=\"color: #ffcc99;\">26 Feb 1998</span> - <a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/tripreport/aruba-26-february-1998\">Baby Beach, Aruba</a> - Total -  3:34</strong></h4>\r\n<h4><s