,0),(2530,5,'2012-09-14 23:53:49','2012-09-15 03:53:49','<p style=\"text-align: center;\">The Great Australian Eclipse is still a few weeks away.   Until then, you\'ll have to make do with this ...</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/wp-content/uploads/Dyer_Libya_600_credit.jpg\" alt=\"dyer libya wide credit\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Totality in Libya 2006 - thanks to the keen eye of Canadian astro-photographer Alan Dyer.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nIt\'s hard to say what makes the best eclipse photographs.  The events are so incredibly dynamic, emotional and high contrast in nature that any favourite images are completely subjective.  But in a sense, that\'s why it\'s so cool.  The experience simply can\'t be captured and put away for later.  But one thing is certain: some images come closer than others in doing just that.  And this is one of them.  As a veteran of 18 solar eclipses - and a consumer of tens of thousands of eclipse images - I can say that the truth and the excitement contained in this shot by Alan Dyer is rare.  And it\'s one of my all-time faves.  I\'m keeping my fingers crossed we all get photo opportunities like this in November.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://eclipseguy.dev/news/total-eclipse-in-2012\">Here</a> are my plans for the next total eclipse of the sun.','Best Eclipse Photos ',0,'What makes a great eclipse photograph? ','publish','open','open','','best-eclipse-photos','','\nhttp://eclipseguy.dev/news/total-eclipse-in-2012','2012-09-15 17:42:49','2012-09-15 21:42:49','',0,'http://eclipseguy.dev/?p=2530',0,'post','',0),(2531,5,'2012-09-14 23:10:17','2012-09-15 03:10:17','','Best Eclipse Photos ',0,'','inherit','open','open','','2530-revision','','','2012-09-14 23:10:17','2012-09-15 03:10:17','',2530,'http://eclipseguy.dev/uncategorized/2530-revision',0,'revision','',0),(2532,5,'2012-09-14 23:24:27','2012-09-15 03:24:27','<p style=\"text-align: center;\"